import re

# AI keywords
ai_keywords = [
    "computer", "software", "data", "analyst", "machine learning",
    "artificial intelligence", "technology", "engineer", "developer",
    "programmer", "tech", "cybersecurity", "database", "systems"
]
pattern = re.compile(r"\b(" + "|".join(ai_keywords) + r")\b")

# Function to create AI-Relevant column
def mark_ai_relevant(df):
    df_ai = df.copy()
    df_ai["AI_Relevant"] = df_ai["Occupation"].str.lower().apply(lambda x: bool(pattern.search(x)))
    return df_ai

# Create AI-relevant datasets
data_2012_ai = mark_ai_relevant(data_2012)
data_2016_ai = mark_ai_relevant(data_2016)
data_2020_ai = mark_ai_relevant(data_2020)
data_2024_ai = mark_ai_relevant(data_2024)

# Compute and display unique AI-relevant occupations clearly by year
for year, df_ai in zip([2012, 2016, 2020, 2024],
                       [data_2012_ai, data_2016_ai, data_2020_ai, data_2024_ai]):
    unique_occupations = df_ai.loc[df_ai['AI_Relevant'], 'Occupation'].unique()
    unique_count = len(unique_occupations)

    print("="*50)
    print(f"Year: {year}")
    print(f"Total unique AI-relevant occupations: {unique_count}\n")
    print("List of AI-relevant occupations:")
    for occ in unique_occupations:
        print(f"- {occ}")
    print("="*50 + "\n")

ai_keywords_extended = [
    "computer", "software", "data", "analyst", "machine learning",
    "artificial intelligence", "technology", "engineer", "developer",
    "programmer", "tech", "cybersecurity", "database", "systems",
    "automation", "algorithm", "analytics", "statistician", "actuary",
    "information systems", "it consultant", "business systems", "research",
    "audit", "auditor", "intelligence", "statistical", "systems",
    "technologist"
]

# Compile regex pattern (case-insensitive)
pattern_extended = re.compile(r"\b(" + "|".join(ai_keywords_extended) + r")\b", flags=re.IGNORECASE)

# List of datasets and years
datasets = [
    (2012, data_2012),
    (2016, data_2016),
    (2020, data_2020),
    (2024, data_2024)
]

# Apply AI filter and print results
for year, df in datasets:
    df_ai = df.copy()
    df_ai['AI_Relevant'] = df_ai['Occupation'].apply(lambda x: bool(pattern_extended.search(x)))

    total_rows = df_ai['AI_Relevant'].sum()
    unique_occupations = df_ai.loc[df_ai['AI_Relevant'], 'Occupation'].nunique()
    occupations_list = sorted(df_ai.loc[df_ai['AI_Relevant'], 'Occupation'].unique())

    print(f"\n{'='*50}")
    print(f"Year: {year}")
    print(f"Total AI-relevant rows: {total_rows}")
    print(f"Unique AI-relevant occupations: {unique_occupations}")
    print("List of AI-relevant occupations:")
    for occ in occupations_list:
        print(f"- {occ}")

def ai_wage_growth_table_clean_annual(datasets, ai_keywords, wage_column="Avg_Wage"):
    """
    Returns a cleaned AI-relevant wage growth table with duplicates aggregated,
    hourly wages converted to annual if needed, and occupations title-cased for readability.
    """
    pattern = re.compile(r"\b(" + "|".join(ai_keywords) + r")\b", flags=re.IGNORECASE)
    frames = []

    for year, df in datasets.items():
        df_copy = df.copy()

        # Ensure wage column is numeric
        df_copy[wage_column] = pd.to_numeric(df_copy[wage_column], errors='coerce')

        # Convert hourly wages to annual if below 200 (typical threshold)
        df_copy[wage_column] = df_copy[wage_column].apply(
            lambda x: x*40*52 if pd.notnull(x) and x < 200 else x
        )

        # Filter AI-relevant occupations
        df_copy = df_copy[df_copy['Occupation'].str.contains(pattern, na=False)]

        # Aggregate Avg_Wage across provinces/regions
        df_grouped = df_copy.groupby('Occupation')[wage_column].mean().reset_index()
        df_grouped.rename(columns={wage_column: str(year)}, inplace=True)
        frames.append(df_grouped)

    # Merge all years on Occupation
    growth_table = frames[0]
    for df_year in frames[1:]:
        growth_table = pd.merge(growth_table, df_year, on="Occupation", how="outer")

    # Standardize occupation names
    growth_table['Occupation_clean'] = growth_table['Occupation'].str.lower().str.strip()

    # Convert all wage columns to numeric (after merge)
    for col in growth_table.columns:
        if col != 'Occupation_clean':
            growth_table[col] = pd.to_numeric(growth_table[col], errors='coerce')

    # Aggregate duplicates by taking mean across same occupation
    growth_table = growth_table.groupby('Occupation_clean').mean().reset_index()

    # Title-case occupation names
    growth_table['Occupation'] = growth_table['Occupation_clean'].str.title()

    # Drop helper column
    growth_table.drop(columns=['Occupation_clean'], inplace=True)

    # Map similar occupations to a standard name
    occupation_map = {
        "Computer Engineers (Except Software Engineers And Designers)": "Computer Engineers (Except Software Engineers)",
        "Computer Engineers (Except Software Engineers)": "Computer Engineers (Except Software Engineers)",
        "Computer Network And Web Technicians": "Computer Network Technicians",
        "Computer Network Technicians": "Computer Network Technicians",
        "Software Engineers": "Software Engineers And Designers",
        "Software Engineers And Designers": "Software Engineers And Designers",
    }
    growth_table['Occupation_standard'] = growth_table['Occupation'].replace(occupation_map)

    # Aggregate duplicates again by standard occupation
    years_list = ['2012', '2016', '2020', '2024']
    df_final = growth_table.groupby('Occupation_standard')[years_list].mean().reset_index()

    # Sort & reset index
    df_final.sort_values('Occupation_standard', inplace=True)
    df_final.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

    # Round all wage columns to 0 decimal places
    df_final[years_list] = df_final[years_list].round(0)

    # Optional: convert to integer type (keeps NaN)
    df_final[years_list] = df_final[years_list].astype('Int64')

    return df_final

datasets_dict = {
    2012: data_2012,
    2016: data_2016,
    2020: data_2020,
    2024: data_2024
}

df_final_numeric = ai_wage_growth_table_clean_annual(datasets_dict, ai_keywords_extended)

# Round wages to 0 decimals and convert to Int64
years = ['2012', '2016', '2020', '2024']
df_final_numeric[years] = df_final_numeric[years].round(0).astype('Int64')

display(df_final_numeric)


# Copy the cleaned numeric table
df_growth = df_final_numeric.copy()

# Calculate interval growths
df_growth['% Growth (20122016)'] = ((df_growth['2016'] - df_growth['2012']) / df_growth['2012'] * 100).where(
    df_growth['2012'].notna() & df_growth['2016'].notna(), pd.NA)

df_growth['% Growth (20162020)'] = ((df_growth['2020'] - df_growth['2016']) / df_growth['2016'] * 100).where(
    df_growth['2016'].notna() & df_growth['2020'].notna(), pd.NA)

df_growth['% Growth (20202024)'] = ((df_growth['2024'] - df_growth['2020']) / df_growth['2020'] * 100).where(
    df_growth['2020'].notna() & df_growth['2024'].notna(), pd.NA)

df_growth['% Growth (20122024)'] = ((df_growth['2024'] - df_growth['2012']) / df_growth['2012'] * 100).where(
    df_growth['2012'].notna() & df_growth['2024'].notna(), pd.NA)

# Round all % Growth columns to 0 decimal places
growth_cols = ['% Growth (20122016)', '% Growth (20162020)',
               '% Growth (20202024)', '% Growth (20122024)']
df_growth[growth_cols] = df_growth[growth_cols].round(0)

# =============================================================================
# INFLATION-ADJUSTED WAGE GROWTH ANALYSIS
# =============================================================================

# Official CPI values for Canada (2002=100 base, annual average)
# Source: Statistics Canada Table 18-10-0005-01
cpi = {
    2012: 116.7,
    2016: 120.7,
    2020: 130.4,
    2024: 151.9  # Annual average for 2024
}

# Create a copy of the cleaned AI wage table for inflation adjustment
df_inflation = df_final_numeric.copy()

# Convert all wages to 2024 dollars (real wages)
print("Converting all wages to 2024 constant dollars...")
print(f"\nCPI Values Used (2002=100 base):")
for year, value in cpi.items():
    print(f"  {year}: {value}")

for year in ['2012', '2016', '2020', '2024']:
    year_int = int(year)
    # Adjust wages to 2024 dollars: wage_2024 = wage_year * (CPI_2024 / CPI_year)
    df_inflation[f'{year}_Real'] = (df_inflation[year] * (cpi[2024] / cpi[year_int])).round(0)

# Calculate Real (Inflation-Adjusted) Growth Rates
print("\nCalculating inflation-adjusted growth rates...")

#2012 to 2016
df_inflation['Real_Growth_2012-2016 (%)'] = (
    ((df_inflation['2016_Real'] - df_inflation['2012_Real']) / df_inflation['2012_Real'] * 100)
    .where(df_inflation['2012_Real'].notna() & df_inflation['2016_Real'].notna(), pd.NA)
).round(1)

#2016 to 2020
df_inflation['Real_Growth_2016-2020 (%)'] = (
    ((df_inflation['2020_Real'] - df_inflation['2016_Real']) / df_inflation['2016_Real'] * 100)
    .where(df_inflation['2016_Real'].notna() & df_inflation['2020_Real'].notna(), pd.NA)
).round(1)

#2020 to 2024
df_inflation['Real_Growth_2020-2024 (%)'] = (
    ((df_inflation['2024_Real'] - df_inflation['2020_Real']) / df_inflation['2020_Real'] * 100)
    .where(df_inflation['2020_Real'].notna() & df_inflation['2024_Real'].notna(), pd.NA)
).round(1)

#2012 to 2024
df_inflation['Real_Growth_2012-2024 (%)'] = (
    ((df_inflation['2024_Real'] - df_inflation['2012_Real']) / df_inflation['2012_Real'] * 100)
    .where(df_inflation['2012_Real'].notna() & df_inflation['2024_Real'].notna(), pd.NA)
).round(1)

#Display the inflation-adjusted table
print("\n" + "="*80)
print("INFLATION-ADJUSTED WAGE ANALYSIS (All values in 2024 constant dollars)")
print("="*80)
display(df_inflation)

# Create a cleaner summary table with both nominal and real wages side by side
df_summary = df_inflation[[
    'Occupation_standard',
    '2012', '2012_Real',
    '2016', '2016_Real',
    '2020', '2020_Real',
    '2024', '2024_Real',
    'Real_Growth_2012-2016 (%)',
    'Real_Growth_2016-2020 (%)',
    'Real_Growth_2020-2024 (%)',
    'Real_Growth_2012-2024 (%)'
]].copy()

# Rename columns for clarity
df_summary.columns = [
    'Occupation',
    '2012 (Nominal)', '2012 (2024$)',
    '2016 (Nominal)', '2016 (2024$)',
    '2020 (Nominal)', '2020 (2024$)',
    '2024 (Nominal)', '2024 (Actual)',
    'Real Growth 2012-16 (%)',
    'Real Growth 2016-20 (%)',
    'Real Growth 2020-24 (%)',
    'Total Real Growth 2012-24 (%)'
]

print("\n" + "="*80)
print("SUMMARY: Nominal vs Real Wages (2024 Constant Dollars)")
print("="*80)
display(df_summary)

# Export to Excel with multiple sheets
with pd.ExcelWriter("AI_Wage_Growth_With_Inflation_Analysis.xlsx", engine='openpyxl') as writer:
    # Sheet 1: Full inflation-adjusted data
    df_inflation.to_excel(writer, sheet_name='Inflation_Adjusted', index=False)

    # Sheet 2: Clean summary

    # Sheet 3: Nominal growth (from earlier)

print("\n" + "="*80)
print("Creating Visualization 1: Real Wage Growth by Occupation (with Non-AI benchmark)")
print("="*80)

# Get AI occupations real growth (from your existing df_inflation)
ai_occupations = df_inflation[['Occupation_standard', 'Real_Growth_2012-2024 (%)']].dropna()
ai_occupations = ai_occupations.sort_values('Real_Growth_2012-2024 (%)', ascending=True)
ai_occupations['Type'] = 'AI-Related'

# Calculate AVERAGE real growth for Non-AI occupations
# Use the SAME methodology as your ai_wage_growth_table_clean_annual function

# Step 1: Get non-AI filtered data
non_ai_filter_2012 = ~data_2012['Occupation'].apply(
    lambda x: bool(pattern_extended.search(str(x))) if pd.notna(x) else False
)
non_ai_filter_2024 = ~data_2024['Occupation'].apply(
    lambda x: bool(pattern_extended.search(str(x))) if pd.notna(x) else False
)

# Step 2: Get Avg_Wage and apply the SAME hourly->annual conversion
non_ai_2012_wages = data_2012[non_ai_filter_2012]['Avg_Wage'].copy()
non_ai_2024_wages = data_2024[non_ai_filter_2024]['Avg_Wage'].copy()

# Apply same conversion logic
non_ai_2012_wages = non_ai_2012_wages.apply(lambda x: x*40*52 if pd.notnull(x) and x < 200 else x)
non_ai_2024_wages = non_ai_2024_wages.apply(lambda x: x*40*52 if pd.notnull(x) and x < 200 else x)

# Step 3: Calculate median
non_ai_2012 = non_ai_2012_wages.median()
non_ai_2024 = non_ai_2024_wages.median()

print(f"\nNon-AI 2012 median wage (annual): ${non_ai_2012:.2f}")
print(f"Non-AI 2024 median wage (annual): ${non_ai_2024:.2f}")

# Step 4: Convert 2012 to real (2024 dollars)
non_ai_2012_real = non_ai_2012 * (cpi[2024] / cpi[2012])

# Step 5: Calculate real growth
non_ai_real_growth = ((non_ai_2024 - non_ai_2012_real) / non_ai_2012_real * 100)

print(f"Non-AI 2012 real (2024$): ${non_ai_2012_real:.2f}")
print(f"Calculated Non-AI Average Real Growth: {non_ai_real_growth:.1f}%")

# Create a benchmark row
non_ai_benchmark = pd.DataFrame({
    'Occupation_standard': ['Average: All Non-AI Occupations'],  # Removed stars
    'Real_Growth_2012-2024 (%)': [non_ai_real_growth],
    'Type': ['Non-AI Benchmark']
})

# Combine AI occupations with non-AI benchmark
combined_data = pd.concat([ai_occupations, non_ai_benchmark], ignore_index=True)
combined_data = combined_data.sort_values('Real_Growth_2012-2024 (%)', ascending=True)

# Create visualization with extended x-axis
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 10))

# Create horizontal bars
y_pos = range(len(combined_data))

for i, (idx, row) in enumerate(combined_data.iterrows()):
    value = row['Real_Growth_2012-2024 (%)']
    is_benchmark = row['Type'] == 'Non-AI Benchmark'

    if is_benchmark:
        color = '#6b6b6b'  # Deeper gray (was #9e9e9e)
        edge_color = '#2b2b2b'  # Darker edge (was #424242)
        line_width = 2.5  # Slightly thinner (was 3)
        alpha = 0.85  # Slightly more opaque
    else:
        if value > 0:
            color = '#99f7c8'
            edge_color = 'black'
            line_width = 1.5
            alpha = 0.9
        else:
            color = '#f79999'
            edge_color = 'black'
            line_width = 1.5
            alpha = 0.9

    ax.barh(i, value, color=color, alpha=alpha, edgecolor=edge_color, linewidth=line_width)

# Add value labels
for i, (idx, row) in enumerate(combined_data.iterrows()):
    value = row['Real_Growth_2012-2024 (%)']

    if row['Type'] == 'Non-AI Benchmark':
        # Simpler styling - no box, just bold text
        ax.text(value + 0.8 if value > 0 else value - 0.8, i, f'{value:.1f}%',
                va='center', ha='left' if value > 0 else 'right',
                fontsize=10, fontweight='bold', color='#2b2b2b')
    else:
        ax.text(value + 0.5 if value > 0 else value - 0.5, i, f'{value:.1f}%',
                va='center', ha='left' if value > 0 else 'right',
                fontsize=9, fontweight='bold')

# Customize y-axis labels (no stars, just slightly bold for benchmark)
y_labels = []
for idx, row in combined_data.iterrows():
    y_labels.append(row['Occupation_standard'])

ax.set_yticks(y_pos)
ax.set_yticklabels(y_labels, fontsize=9)

# Make Non-AI benchmark label slightly bold (not too much)
for i, (label, (idx, row)) in enumerate(zip(ax.get_yticklabels(), combined_data.iterrows())):
    if row['Type'] == 'Non-AI Benchmark':
        label.set_fontweight('semibold')  # Less bold than before

# Prepare AI wage data - use occupation-level wages (not individual entries)
ai_wage_data = []
for year in ['2012', '2016', '2020', '2024']:
    wages = df_final_numeric[year].dropna().values
    for wage in wages:
        ai_wage_data.append({'Year': year, 'Wage': float(wage), 'Type': 'AI-Related'})

print(f"AI data points: {len(ai_wage_data)}")

# Prepare Non-AI wage data - aggregate by occupation first
non_ai_wage_data = []
for year_int in [2012, 2016, 2020, 2024]:
    year_data = datasets_dict[year_int]

    # Filter Non-AI occupations
    non_ai_filter = ~year_data['Occupation'].apply(
        lambda x: bool(pattern_extended.search(str(x))) if pd.notna(x) else False
    )

    non_ai_subset = year_data[non_ai_filter].copy()

    # Get wages and apply conversion
    non_ai_subset['Avg_Wage_Converted'] = non_ai_subset['Avg_Wage'].apply(
        lambda x: x*40*52 if pd.notnull(x) and x < 200 else x
    )

    # Group by occupation and take median (to reduce noise)
    occupation_medians = non_ai_subset.groupby('Occupation')['Avg_Wage_Converted'].median()

    for wage in occupation_medians.dropna():
        if wage > 0:  # Filter out invalid wages
            non_ai_wage_data.append({'Year': str(year_int), 'Wage': float(wage), 'Type': 'Non-AI'})

print(f"Non-AI data points: {len(non_ai_wage_data)}")

# Combine both datasets
all_wage_data = ai_wage_data + non_ai_wage_data
df_wages_long = pd.DataFrame(all_wage_data)

import urllib.request
import zipfile
import os

print("DOWNLOADING STATCAN DATA...")
print("="*80)

# Download Table 14-10-0417-01 (Employee wages by occupation, annual - Gender/Province data)
print("\n1. Downloading Gender/Province wage data (Table 14-10-0417-01)...")
url_gender = "https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/tbl/csv/14100417-eng.zip"

try:
    urllib.request.urlretrieve(url_gender, "data/14100417-eng.zip")

    # Extract the ZIP file
    with zipfile.ZipFile("data/14100417-eng.zip", 'r') as zip_ref:
        zip_ref.extractall("data/gender_province")

    print(" Downloaded and extracted successfully!")
    print(f"  Files saved to: data/gender_province/")

    # List the extracted files
    files = os.listdir("data/gender_province")
    print(f"  Extracted files: {files}")

except Exception as e:
    print(f" Error downloading: {e}")


# Download Table 14-10-0064-01 (Employment by industry/region)
print("\n2. Downloading Industry/Region data (Table 14-10-0064-01)...")

df_gender_filtered = df_gender[
    (df_gender['REF_DATE'].isin(years_of_interest)) &
    (df_gender['Wages'].isin(['Average hourly wage rate', 'Median hourly wage rate'])) &
    (df_gender['Age group'] == '15 years and over') &  # Focus on all ages
    (df_gender['Gender'].isin(['Men+', 'Women+']))  # Only Men and Women
].copy()

# =============================================================================
# IMPROVED AI FILTER - Works with StatCan NOC format
# =============================================================================

def is_ai_relevant_noc(noc_text):
    """
    Check if NOC occupation is AI-related
    Works with StatCan format like: 'Computer programmers and interactive media developers [2174]'
    """
    if pd.isna(noc_text):
        return False

    noc_str = str(noc_text).lower()

    # List of AI-related keywords (same as main analysis)
    ai_keywords = [
        "computer", "software", "data", "analyst", "machine learning",
        "artificial intelligence", "technology", "engineer", "developer",
        "programmer", "tech", "cybersecurity", "database", "systems",
        "automation", "algorithm", "analytics", "statistician", "actuary",
        "information systems", "it consultant", "business systems",
        "audit", "auditor", "intelligence", "statistical",
        "technologist", "information technology", "web", "network",
        "telecommunications", "digital", "electronic"
    ]

    # Check if any keyword appears in the NOC description
    for keyword in ai_keywords:
        if keyword in noc_str:
            return True

    return False

# Apply improved AI filter
df_gender_filtered['AI_Relevant'] = df_gender_filtered['National Occupational Classification (NOC)'].apply(is_ai_relevant_noc)

print(f"\n Updated AI filter applied")
print(f"  AI-relevant occupations found: {df_gender_filtered['AI_Relevant'].sum()} rows")

# Show sample AI-relevant occupations
if df_gender_filtered['AI_Relevant'].sum() > 0:
    print(f"\nSample AI-relevant NOC occupations:")
    ai_sample = df_gender_filtered[df_gender_filtered['AI_Relevant']]['National Occupational Classification (NOC)'].unique()[:10]
    for i, occ in enumerate(ai_sample, 1):
        print(f"  {i}. {occ}")
else:
    print("\n WARNING: Still no AI occupations found. Check keywords.")

# =============================================================================
# VISUALIZATION 1 - OPTION A: Gender Wage Analysis (COMPLETELY FIXED - NO OVERLAP)
# =============================================================================

print("\n" + "="*80)
print("Creating Visualization 1 - Option A: Gender Wage Analysis (COMPLETELY FIXED)")
print("="*80)

# Calculate average hourly wages by gender and year for AI occupations
gender_time_data = df_gender_filtered[
    (df_gender_filtered['AI_Relevant'] == True) &
    (df_gender_filtered['Wages'] == 'Average hourly wage rate') &
    (df_gender_filtered['GEO'] == 'Canada')
].groupby(['REF_DATE', 'Gender'])['VALUE'].mean().reset_index()

# Pivot for easier plotting
gender_time_pivot = gender_time_data.pivot(index='REF_DATE', columns='Gender', values='VALUE')

# Calculate real wages (inflation-adjusted to 2024 dollars)
gender_time_pivot['Men+_Real'] = gender_time_pivot['Men+'] * (cpi[2024] / gender_time_pivot.index.map(cpi))
gender_time_pivot['Women+_Real'] = gender_time_pivot['Women+'] * (cpi[2024] / gender_time_pivot.index.map(cpi))

# Calculate growth rates (year-over-year relative to 2012)
base_men_real = gender_time_pivot.loc[2012, 'Men+_Real']
base_women_real = gender_time_pivot.loc[2012, 'Women+_Real']

gender_time_pivot['Men_Growth_%'] = ((gender_time_pivot['Men+_Real'] - base_men_real) / base_men_real * 100)
gender_time_pivot['Women_Growth_%'] = ((gender_time_pivot['Women+_Real'] - base_women_real) / base_women_real * 100)

# Calculate absolute dollar gap
gender_time_pivot['Dollar_Gap'] = gender_time_pivot['Men+'] - gender_time_pivot['Women+']
gender_time_pivot['Dollar_Gap_Real'] = gender_time_pivot['Men+_Real'] - gender_time_pivot['Women+_Real']

# Create visualization with MORE spacing to prevent overlap
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16, 14))
gs = fig.add_gridspec(2, 2, hspace=0.45, wspace=0.25, top=0.91, bottom=0.08, left=0.08, right=0.95)

# Top-left: Nominal wages
ax1 = fig.add_subplot(gs[0, 0])
ax1.plot(gender_time_pivot.index, gender_time_pivot['Men+'],
         marker='o', linewidth=3, markersize=10, label='Men (Nominal)',
         color='#3498db', alpha=0.8)
ax1.plot(gender_time_pivot.index, gender_time_pivot['Women+'],
         marker='s', linewidth=3, markersize=10, label='Women (Nominal)',
         color='#e74c3c', alpha=0.8)

for year in gender_time_pivot.index:
    men_val = gender_time_pivot.loc[year, 'Men+']
    women_val = gender_time_pivot.loc[year, 'Women+']
    ax1.text(year, men_val + 1.2, f'${men_val:.2f}', ha='center',
             fontsize=9, color='#3498db', fontweight='bold')
    ax1.text(year, women_val - 1.2, f'${women_val:.2f}', ha='center',
             fontsize=9, color='#e74c3c', fontweight='bold')

ax1.set_xlabel('Year', fontsize=11, fontweight='bold')
ax1.set_ylabel('Average Hourly Wage ($)', fontsize=11, fontweight='bold')
ax1.set_title('Nominal Wages - AI Occupations', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold', pad=12)
ax1.legend(loc='upper left', fontsize=10, frameon=True, shadow=True)
ax1.grid(True, alpha=0.3, linestyle='--')
ax1.set_xticks(gender_time_pivot.index)
ax1.set_ylim(bottom=gender_time_pivot[['Men+', 'Women+']].min().min() - 3,
              top=gender_time_pivot[['Men+', 'Women+']].max().max() + 4)

# Top-right: Real wages (2024 dollars)
ax2 = fig.add_subplot(gs[0, 1])
ax2.plot(gender_time_pivot.index, gender_time_pivot['Men+_Real'],
         marker='o', linewidth=3, markersize=10, label='Men (Real, 2024$)',
         color='#2980b9', alpha=0.8)
ax2.plot(gender_time_pivot.index, gender_time_pivot['Women+_Real'],
         marker='s', linewidth=3, markersize=10, label='Women (Real, 2024$)',
         color='#c0392b', alpha=0.8)

for year in gender_time_pivot.index:
    men_val = gender_time_pivot.loc[year, 'Men+_Real']
    women_val = gender_time_pivot.loc[year, 'Women+_Real']
    ax2.text(year, men_val + 1.2, f'${men_val:.2f}', ha='center',
             fontsize=9, color='#2980b9', fontweight='bold')
    ax2.text(year, women_val - 1.2, f'${women_val:.2f}', ha='center',
             fontsize=9, color='#c0392b', fontweight='bold')

ax2.set_xlabel('Year', fontsize=11, fontweight='bold')
ax2.set_ylabel('Average Hourly Wage (2024 $)', fontsize=11, fontweight='bold')
ax2.set_title('Real Wages (Inflation-Adjusted) - AI Occupations',
              fontsize=12, fontweight='bold', pad=12)
ax2.legend(loc='upper left', fontsize=10, frameon=True, shadow=True)
ax2.grid(True, alpha=0.3, linestyle='--')
ax2.set_xticks(gender_time_pivot.index)
ax2.set_ylim(bottom=gender_time_pivot[['Men+_Real', 'Women+_Real']].min().min() - 3,
              top=gender_time_pivot[['Men+_Real', 'Women+_Real']].max().max() + 4)

# Bottom-left: Real wage growth %
ax3 = fig.add_subplot(gs[1, 0])
ax3.plot(gender_time_pivot.index, gender_time_pivot['Men_Growth_%'],
         marker='o', linewidth=3, markersize=10, label='Men',
         color='#3498db', alpha=0.8)
ax3.plot(gender_time_pivot.index, gender_time_pivot['Women_Growth_%'],
         marker='s', linewidth=3, markersize=10, label='Women',
         color='#e74c3c', alpha=0.8)

for year in gender_time_pivot.index:
    men_growth = gender_time_pivot.loc[year, 'Men_Growth_%']
    women_growth = gender_time_pivot.loc[year, 'Women_Growth_%']

    if men_growth > women_growth:
        ax3.text(year, men_growth + 1.5, f'{men_growth:.1f}%', ha='center',
                 fontsize=9, color='#3498db', fontweight='bold')
        ax3.text(year, women_growth - 1.5, f'{women_growth:.1f}%', ha='center',
                 fontsize=9, color='#e74c3c', fontweight='bold')
    else:
        ax3.text(year, men_growth - 1.5, f'{men_growth:.1f}%', ha='center',

# VISUALIZATION 4: Wage Growth by Province

print("\n" + "="*80)
print("Creating Visualization 4: Real Wage Growth by Province")
print("="*80)

# Calculate average wages by province for 2012 and 2024
province_wages = df_gender_filtered[
    (df_gender_filtered['REF_DATE'].isin([2012, 2024])) &
    (df_gender_filtered['Wages'] == 'Average hourly wage rate') &
    (df_gender_filtered['GEO'].isin(provinces)) &
    (df_gender_filtered['Gender'] == 'Men+')  # Use Men+ to avoid double counting
].groupby(['GEO', 'REF_DATE'])['VALUE'].mean().reset_index()

# Pivot to get 2012 and 2024 side by side
province_wages_pivot = province_wages.pivot(index='GEO', columns='REF_DATE', values='VALUE')

# Apply inflation adjustment
province_wages_pivot['2012_Real'] = province_wages_pivot[2012] * (cpi[2024] / cpi[2012])
province_wages_pivot['2024_Real'] = province_wages_pivot[2024]

# Calculate real growth
province_wages_pivot['Real_Growth_%'] = ((province_wages_pivot['2024_Real'] - province_wages_pivot['2012_Real']) /
                                          province_wages_pivot['2012_Real'] * 100)

# Sort by growth
province_wages_pivot = province_wages_pivot.sort_values('Real_Growth_%', ascending=True)

# Create visualization
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 8))

# Positive = #99f7c8 (mint green), Negative = #f79999 (light red)
colors = ['#99f7c8' if x > 0 else '#f79999' for x in province_wages_pivot['Real_Growth_%']]
bars = ax.barh(province_wages_pivot.index, province_wages_pivot['Real_Growth_%'],
               color=colors, alpha=0.9, edgecolor='black', linewidth=1.5)

# Add value labels
for i, (idx, row) in enumerate(province_wages_pivot.iterrows()):
    value = row['Real_Growth_%']
    ax.text(value + 0.5 if value > 0 else value - 0.5, i, f'{value:.1f}%',
            va='center', ha='left' if value > 0 else 'right',
            fontsize=10, fontweight='bold')

ax.axvline(x=0, color='black', linestyle='-', linewidth=1.5)
ax.set_xlabel('Real Wage Growth 2012-2024 (%)', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
ax.set_title('Inflation-Adjusted Wage Growth by Province (2012-2024)\nAll Occupations, 2024 Constant Dollars',
             fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', pad=20)
ax.grid(axis='x', alpha=0.3)

# Add cumulative inflation reference
cumulative_inflation = ((cpi[2024] - cpi[2012]) / cpi[2012] * 100)
ax.axvline(x=cumulative_inflation, color='red', linestyle='--', linewidth=2, alpha=0.7,
           label=f'Cumulative Inflation ({cumulative_inflation:.1f}%)')
ax.legend(loc='lower right', fontsize=10)

plt.tight_layout()

    (df_gender_filtered['Wages'] == 'Average hourly wage rate') &

].groupby(['GEO', 'REF_DATE', 'Gender'])['VALUE'].mean().reset_index()

# Pivot to calculate gap

gap_data = []
for province in provinces:
    for year in years_of_interest:
        try:
            men_wage = heatmap_pivot.loc[province, (year, 'Men+')]
            women_wage = heatmap_pivot.loc[province, (year, 'Women+')]
            gap = ((men_wage - women_wage) / men_wage * 100)
            gap_data.append({'Province': province, 'Year': year, 'Wage_Gap_%': gap})
        except:
            gap_data.append({'Province': province, 'Year': year, 'Wage_Gap_%': np.nan})

gap_df = pd.DataFrame(gap_data)
gap_matrix = gap_df.pivot(index='Province', columns='Year', values='Wage_Gap_%')

# Check actual range to set appropriate color scale
actual_min = gap_matrix.min().min()
actual_max = gap_matrix.max().max()

# Create heatmap with ADJUSTED range (narrower for better contrast)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 8))

sns.heatmap(gap_matrix, annot=True, fmt='.1f', cmap='RdYlGn_r',
            center=(actual_min + actual_max) / 2,  # Center at midpoint
            cbar_kws={'label': 'Gender Wage Gap (%)'},
            linewidths=0.5, linecolor='white', ax=ax,
            vmin=actual_min - 2, vmax=actual_max + 2)  # Tighter range

# FIXED TITLE - No special characters, clear explanation
ax.set_title('Gender Wage Gap Across Provinces Over Time\nMen Earn This Percent More Than Women',
             fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', pad=20)
ax.set_xlabel('Year', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
ax.set_ylabel('Province', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')

# VISUALIZATION 8: Provincial Gender Wage Growth - Nominal vs Real
# =============================================================================

print("\n" + "="*80)
print("Creating Visualization 8: Provincial Gender Equity - Nominal vs Real Growth")
print("="*80)

# Calculate wage growth by province and gender (2012-2024)
province_gender_growth = []

for province in provinces:
    for gender in ['Men+', 'Women+']:
        prov_gender_data = df_gender_filtered[
            (df_gender_filtered['REF_DATE'].isin([2012, 2024])) &
            (df_gender_filtered['Wages'] == 'Average hourly wage rate') &
            (df_gender_filtered['GEO'] == province) &
            (df_gender_filtered['Gender'] == gender)
        ].groupby('REF_DATE')['VALUE'].mean()

        if 2012 in prov_gender_data.index and 2024 in prov_gender_data.index:
            wage_2012 = prov_gender_data[2012]
            wage_2024 = prov_gender_data[2024]

            # Nominal growth
            nominal_growth = ((wage_2024 - wage_2012) / wage_2012 * 100)

            # Real growth (convert 2012 to 2024 dollars)
            wage_2012_real = wage_2012 * (cpi[2024] / cpi[2012])
            real_growth = ((wage_2024 - wage_2012_real) / wage_2012_real * 100)

            province_gender_growth.append({
                'Province': province,
                'Gender': gender,
                'Nominal_Growth_%': nominal_growth,
                'Real_Growth_%': real_growth
            })

growth_df = pd.DataFrame(province_gender_growth)

# Calculate average real growth for sorting
avg_growth = growth_df.groupby('Province')['Real_Growth_%'].mean().sort_values(ascending=True)
sorted_provinces = avg_growth.index.tolist()

# Calculate cumulative inflation
cumulative_inflation = ((cpi[2024] - cpi[2012]) / cpi[2012] * 100)

# Create visualization with MORE vertical spacing to prevent overlap
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(14, 14))

# INCREASED hspace from 0.35 to 0.50 to prevent title overlap
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.50, top=0.92, bottom=0.08, left=0.12, right=0.95)

# Top: Men's wage growth

width = 0.35

# Men colors: Light blue (#99c8f7) for nominal, DEEPER blue for real
bars1 = ax1.bar(x - width/2, men_growth['Nominal_Growth_%'], width,
                label='Nominal Growth', color='#99c8f7', alpha=0.85, edgecolor='black')
bars2 = ax1.bar(x + width/2, men_growth['Real_Growth_%'], width,
                label='Real Growth (2024$)', color='#5ba3e0', alpha=0.95, edgecolor='black')

# Add cumulative inflation line
ax1.axhline(y=cumulative_inflation, color='red', linestyle='--', linewidth=2,
            alpha=0.7, label=f'Cumulative Inflation ({cumulative_inflation:.1f}%)', zorder=5)
ax1.axhline(y=0, color='black', linestyle='-', linewidth=1.5, alpha=0.6)

ax1.set_ylabel('Wage Growth 2012-2024 (%)', fontsize=13, fontweight='bold')
# REDUCED title padding to prevent overlap
ax1.set_title("Men's Wage Growth by Province: Nominal vs Real (2012-2024)",
              fontsize=13, fontweight='bold', pad=10)
ax1.set_xticks(x)
ax1.set_xticklabels(sorted_provinces, rotation=45, ha='right', fontsize=10)
ax1.legend(loc='upper left', fontsize=11, frameon=True, shadow=True)
ax1.grid(axis='y', alpha=0.3)

# Set y-axis with clean multiples of 5
y_min_men = min(men_growth['Nominal_Growth_%'].min(), men_growth['Real_Growth_%'].min())
y_max_men = max(men_growth['Nominal_Growth_%'].max(), men_growth['Real_Growth_%'].max())

# Round to nearest 5
y_min_rounded = int(y_min_men // 5) * 5 - 5

# Bottom: Women's wage growth
women_growth = growth_df[growth_df['Gender'] == 'Women+'].set_index('Province').loc[sorted_provinces]

ax2 = axes[1]

# Women colors: Light pink (#f799c8) for nominal, DEEPER pink for real
bars3 = ax2.bar(x - width/2, women_growth['Nominal_Growth_%'], width,
                label='Nominal Growth', color='#f799c8', alpha=0.85, edgecolor='black')
bars4 = ax2.bar(x + width/2, women_growth['Real_Growth_%'], width,
                label='Real Growth (2024$)', color='#f55d9a', alpha=0.95, edgecolor='black')

# Add cumulative inflation line
ax2.axhline(y=cumulative_inflation, color='red', linestyle='--', linewidth=2,
            alpha=0.7, label=f'Cumulative Inflation ({cumulative_inflation:.1f}%)', zorder=5)
ax2.axhline(y=0, color='black', linestyle='-', linewidth=1.5, alpha=0.6)

ax2.set_ylabel('Wage Growth 2012-2024 (%)', fontsize=13, fontweight='bold')
# REDUCED title padding to prevent overlap
ax2.set_title("Women's Wage Growth by Province: Nominal vs Real (2012-2024)",
              fontsize=13, fontweight='bold', pad=10)
ax2.set_xticks(x)
ax2.set_xticklabels(sorted_provinces, rotation=45, ha='right', fontsize=10)
ax2.legend(loc='upper left', fontsize=11, frameon=True, shadow=True)
ax2.grid(axis='y', alpha=0.3)

# Set y-axis with clean multiples of 5
y_min_women = min(women_growth['Nominal_Growth_%'].min(), women_growth['Real_Growth_%'].min())
y_max_women = max(women_growth['Nominal_Growth_%'].max(), women_growth['Real_Growth_%'].max())

# Round to nearest 5
y_min_rounded = int(y_min_women // 5) * 5 - 5
y_max_rounded = int(y_max_women // 5) * 5 + 10

ax2.set_ylim(y_min_rounded, y_max_rounded)
ax2.set_yticks(range(y_min_rounded, y_max_rounded + 1, 5))

# Overall title - positioned lower to avoid overlap
plt.suptitle('Provincial Gender Wage Growth Analysis: Impact of Inflation\nAll Occupations, Sorted by Average Real Growth',
             fontsize=15, fontweight='bold', y=0.97)

plt.savefig('Provincial_Gender_Growth_Nominal_vs_Real.png', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
plt.show()

print(" Saved: Provincial_Gender_Growth_Nominal_vs_Real.png")
